nt-size:11.5pt">my appearance before the Home Affairs Select Committee on 16 December.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; text-decoration:underline">Foreign Fighters</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Given the concerns about foreign fighters, what sort of work is the Government doing to identify and monitor UK nationals who travel in order to engage in jihad?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Are social media such as twitter and Facebook being monitored for people who are claiming to engage or have engaged in fighting abroad?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">There have been claims that there is significant "coming and going" from the battlefield with people going to fight for a month or two in Syria and then returning to Britain to rest and recuperate. What legislative means does the Government have at its disposal to stop people returning to Syria? And is the legislation sufficient?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The police and the security and intelligence agencies undertake a number of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">activities to identify, monitor and disrupt UK-Iinked individuals of concern who travel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">abroad to engage in conflict. You will understand why I am unable to provide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">specific details of all of the actions that are being taken for these purposes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">You ask about the legislative means we have at our disposal to stop people from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">returning to Syria. A wide range of offences already exists on the statute books that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">can be used to disrupt travel by such individuals and to manage the risk they may</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">pose on return, including in the Terrorism Acts 2000 and 2006 which provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">extraterritorial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">jurisdiction in relation to certain activities. In particular, where there is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">evidence that individuals are planning, promoting, funding, facilitating or participating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">in terrorist activities overseas - including terrorist fighting - the police and Crown</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Prosecution Service will seek to prosecute them, before they go or on their return.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Where appropriate, consideration will also be given to the use of disruptive powers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">such as asset freezes and Terrorism Prevention and Investigation Measures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">(TPIMS) to disrupt travel and manage the risk posed by returnees who cannot be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">successfully prosecuted , or in the case of foreign nationals, deported. If the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">individual is a dual national, I will consider whether deprivation of their British</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">citizenship is appropriate. Similarly, I may seek to exclude non-nationals from the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">UK on public interest grounds.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">I also have the power to refuse or withdraw passports (under the Royal Prerogative)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">where I believe that a person's activities - past, present or proposed - are so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">undesirable that the grant or continued enjoyment of passport facilities is contrary to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the public interest. New powers to search for, and seize, cancelled passports, as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">well as other invalid travel documents, have been introduced into the Anti-Social</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Behaviour, Crime and Policing Bill.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; text-decoration:underline">Overseas Capacity Building</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Is the Government confident that overseas capacity building programmes have a positive effect on both the host country and in the UK and how is the effectiveness of the individual programmes measured?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Please could you provide a breakdown of the £30 million budget for overseas capacity building detailing what sort of programmes are being run where.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Where are the Government's priority countries in terms of overseas capacity building for the next year?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">As Charles Farr's letter to the Committee of 6 January 201</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> sets out, we do not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">publicly disclose the location, number or purpose of all our capacity building projects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">overseas because they very often have a counter terrorist operational purpose.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">However, as might be expected, and as described in the Foreign Secretary's speech</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">on Countering Terrorism Overseas (14 February 2013), our work focuses in those</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">areas where there is a serious and potentially long-running threat to the UK and our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">interests abroad.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Projects primarily focus on working with police, prosecutors, judges and prison</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">authorities to build their capacity to detain, prosecute and convict terrorists based on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">respect for human rights and the rule of law. Every aspect of this work is closely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">monitored and requires Ministerial oversight and approval.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">For operational and security reasons that you will understand I cannot provide more</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">in-depth detail of the projects or detailed costing breakdown in this letter.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> understand that the Committee has written separately to the Foreign Secretary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">about the cross-Government effort to build capacity overseas in his role as lead</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Minister for that work. In light of that, these additional questions from the Committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">may be better dealt with in more detail in the response to that letter.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; text-decoration:underline">TPIMs</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Are individuals on TPIMs also provided with the necessary support to deradicalise them? Are any of the individuals part of the Channel Programme?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Prevent interventions play a part in operational planning to manage the risk from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">TPIM subjects after the expiry of TPIM measures. It would be inappropriate for me to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">comment on the detail of these plans. None of the TPIM subjects are currently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">suitable for Channel, which is specifically designed for individuals at risk of being</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">drawn into terrorism.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">We note that in response to our request that Mr Farr provide us with the deportation request from the Somaliland Government in relation to Mohammed Ahmed Mohamed, Mr Farr wrote to us saying:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">"As this matter is currently the subject of ongoing civil litigation I cannot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">provide any details further to what I told the Committee. However, I can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">confirm that documents relating to Mohamed's deportation from Somaliland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">were disclosed during open session in the TPIMs proceedings by both the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Government and Mohamed's lawyers. These documents are not in the public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">domain."</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Can we ask you to confirm that a) a deportation request was made by the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Somaliland Government and that b) the Somalian Government refused to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">accept the return of Mr Mohamed to their territory?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">You have asked for sight of official correspondence from the Somaliland government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">in respect of the deportation of Mohammed Ahmed Mohamed. I can confirm that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">documents relating to Mohamed's deportation from Somaliland were disclosed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">during open session in the TPIMs proceedings by both HMG and Mohamed's</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">lawyers. However, as has previously been set out, these documents are not in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">public domain, given the ongoing litigation and as such it would be inappropriate for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">me to comment further on the details.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">As I also indicated at committee, the Government would not normally disclose</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">government to government communications. By routinely doing so we may harm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">future relations with a third state on the basis that all future correspondence will be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">made publically available.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">In respect of Mohamed's return to the UK and as has been set out previously, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">law is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> quite clear on this. Section 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">(1) of the Immigration Act 1971 exempts from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">immigration control persons who have the right of abode. This means that there is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">no legal basis for preventing British citizens, like Mohamed, from returning to the UK,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">whatever the circumstances of their return and whatever their activities abroad. It is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">also important to note that where someone is a British citizen, it is not necessary for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">a foreign government to seek permission for their return.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; text-decoration:underline">Communications data</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">What is the difference between the current data monitoring capabilities of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">GCHQ and those that would have been introduced under the Communications</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Data Bill?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The Draft Communications Data Bill proposed the retention of additional</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">communications data by Communications Service Providers so that with appropriate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">approvals and where necessary and proportionate it could be acquired by law</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">enforcement agencies as part of a specific investigation. GCHQ's core mission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">relates to the gathering of foreign intelligence and they may collect data in relation to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">this function. They are not able to provide the communications data required by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">domestic law enforcement agencies. Further detail on GCHQ's capabilities has been</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">shared with the Intelligence and Security Committee, as this is expressly within</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">their remit.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The Rt Hon Theresa May MP</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Home Secretary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>